pma:database.name: content

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: The piece begins with a portrait of Don Juan, the infamous womanizer. A rapid upward sweep in the strings followed by a falling gesture in the winds brings us to the primary theme, which depicts the Don in all his zesty hedonism. $DJ1.png,
Don Juan Theme,green

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: The Don's first flirtation, foreshadowing the secondary theme.

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: A return of the Don's themes creates a transition to the secondary theme.

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: A lyrical violin melody over a sustained pedal point introduces the Don's first lover.
Love Scene,red

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: Love scene #1, depicted by a lyrical melody for clarinet and horn; also the secondary theme of the sonata form. $DJ2.png,

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: The rendezvous over, the Don takes his leave hastily, disregarding a last entreaty by his lover.

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: Don Juan Theme,green

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: The development section of the sonata form begins with a return of the Don's themes.

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: The Don has found his next romantic victim, whose feeble attempts at resistance are portrayed by the solo flute. $DJ3.png,

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: At last she submits, and Love scene #2 follows, with a famous and tender melody for the oboe.
Love Scene,red

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: Once again the Don makes a hasty retreat.

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: Don Juan New Theme,darkgreen

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: The Don recieves a new theme, played heroically by the horns, as he once again rejects his jilted lover's entreaties. $DJ4.png,

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: Carnival and Depression,darkblue

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: The Don finds himself at a carnival or masked ball, where he reaches the height of his glorious debauchery before the inevitable fall.

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: Don Juan suddenly plunges into a deep and overwhelming depression as he finally comes to grips with the ramifications of his depravity. $DJ5.png,

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: Ghosts of his former mistresses return to haunt the Don.

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: Don Pedro, the son of a nobleman Juan murdered, has returned for vengeance. Don Juan rouses himself from his despondency for a final fight to the death.

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: The recapitulation section of the sonata form. In preparing for battle, the Don's former invincibility has returned. He will easily dispatch Don Pedro. $DJ6.png,
Don Juan Theme,green

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: In the recapitulation, the secondary theme is replaced by the Don's heroic theme from the development section as he prepares for victory.
Don Juan New Theme,darkgreen

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: At the last moment, when victory seems imminent, Juan drops his sword and allows Pedro to run him through. He decides death is preferable to the continuation of his meaningless existence, saying, the fuel is all consumed and the hearth is cold and dark. $DJ7.png,
Don Juan Death,black

table.name: Strauss, Don Juan: Don Juan
table.column: END
